@startuml remote-memory
title Remote memory — node-initiated RPCs mid-CALL (feature 0x01)
hide footbox
skinparam shadowing false

participant "Coordinator\n(owns the regions)" as C
box "wasp node"
participant "network + agent" as N
participant "executor\n(module running)" as E
end box

C -> N : CALL "scale" [ref][n][k]\n(coordinator's seq space)
N -> E : exec queue
activate E

note over C, E
  From here the roles reverse: the **node** asks, the coordinator answers.
  0x4x requests use the node's own seq space, so both directions share the
  one TCP connection without ambiguity. Each request below transits the tx
  queue and blocks the executor on the RPC slot until the reply is routed
  back (or CONFIG_WASP_RPC_TIMEOUT_MS expires).
end note

E -> C : REGION_INFO [region]
C --> E : REGION_DESC [length u32]

E -> C : LOCK [region]
C --> E : LOCK_GRANT [lease_ms u32]
note right of C : lock state lives **only** here;\nthe grant is a lease — it expires\nif the node dies holding it

E -> C : MEM_READ [ref u32][len u32]
C --> E : MEM_DATA [len bytes]
note right of C : bounds-checked on the node first,\nthen authoritatively here

E -> E : compute: buf[i] *= k

E -> C : MEM_WRITE [ref u32][bytes]
C --> E : MEM_ACK
note right of C : the write lands directly in the\ncoordinator's registered bytearray

E -> C : UNLOCK [region]
C --> E : MEM_ACK

E --> N : tx msgq
deactivate E
N --> C : RESULT [WASP_REMOTE_OK]\n(answers the CALL's seq)

== If the coordinator goes silent mid-call ==

C -> N : CALL "scale" …
N -> E : exec queue
activate E
E -> C : MEM_READ [ref][len]
...CONFIG_WASP_RPC_TIMEOUT_MS (5 s) passes, no reply...
E -> E : host call raises a WASM exception\n— the module **traps**
E --> N : tx msgq
deactivate E
N --> C : ERROR [TRAP, "wasp: remote memory RPC failed"]
note over N : the node carries on; a hung\ncoordinator can never wedge it
@enduml
